				<li id="16729466" class="cmnt-root" data="3" data-d="1656922299000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><div class="comment-username">Anonymous</div></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t578345/Magic-Downpour" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">04 Jul 2022 04:11</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=193&p=16729466" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">Fun fact: This spell DOES track. Notice how when you cast it, it turns to face the closest enemy from it? From my observations, it&apos;s usually only one streak of the downpour that tracks in the general direction of whatever the spell is aiming at. I think it&apos;s intentionally designed like this else the bullets would be way too randomized to hit anything. Normally I would say that this spell is kind of lackluster. However, the only saving grace with this spell is that the bullets actually flinches a lot of things, making it a great spell to use closely on bosses like Malenia (especially in co-op since it can interrupt her) where she is very prone to getting staggered. </p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16729466" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#replies-16729466" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Replies (<span class="replies">0</span>)</a><div class="vote pull-right"><section class="t-up"><span></span><p>3</p><i class="add">+1</i